column1: How many people in the US will have received one or more doses of a COVID-19 vaccine as of 31 May 2021, according to the CDC?
column5: ['Fewer than 170,000,000', 'Between 170,000,000 and 180,000,000, inclusive', 'More than 180,000,000 but fewer than 190,000,000', 'Between 190,000,000 and 200,000,000, inclusive', 'More than 200,000,000 but fewer than 210,000,000', 'Between 210,000,000 and 220,000,000, inclusive', 'More than 220,000,000']
column6: ['Technology', 'Society', 'Health']
I think this is going to be very close after all the data comes in, but leaning toward below 170. The last fully reported day is May 25 at 166.2, 6 days left at 600k puts it just below 170.

With today's reporting, and seeing 0.63M/day added for the past week and falling, I don't see how it will be possible to get to 170M. It will be close, but I'm certain it will be under 170M. If 0.63M/day are added for the next 4 days (inc. 3 for back reporting), we'll get to 170.25M. But I just don't see how the number added per day won't fall, both because of the continuing trend and because of the holiday weekend. Yesterday, the projection at yesterday's rate added/week without continued decline was 170.51M; today's projection without continued decline is 170.25M. Tomorrow's projection without continued decline will likely be ~170.0M, with even greater declines from the holiday yet to show up. I think the final number will be closer to 169.0M than to 170.0M.

There are currently approximately 160 million people with 1 dose or more, and the rate is begging to slow down plateau. Most people who want the vaccine have now had it, and most people who remain unvaccinated either don’t want it or are too young. It’s very unlikely that by the end of this month we will see a huge jump in number of vaccines.

Unpredictable...despite Memorial Day, I think 170m+ is a tiny bit more likely. It may remain suspenseful until data accession on June 14 – @belikewater my gut feeling is that it will jump over 170m on June 13 …

Today at 167.73M. 0.57M added in the past day. 0.77M added the day before. 4.42M added in the past week, or 0.63M/day. 4 days left in forecast (inc. 3 for back reporting). 167.73M + 4*0.63M = 170.25M. And, there will likely be fewer vaccines given over Memorial Day weekend, both because doses given are declining and because fewer people will likely get vaccinated over the holiday, although any extra decline won't fully show up in reporting until June 2. My current best guess is that the final number will be between 169.0M and 170.0M.
Gonna be close but I'm hedging that the lag will bring it over the top. Though my three most recent judgements have all said just under 170M. And I did poorly on a similar question.

Today at 167.16M. 0.77M added in the past day, continuing the decline. 4.69M added in the past week, or 0.67M/day. 5 days left in forecast (inc. 3 for back reporting). 167.16M + 5*0.67M = 170.51M. And, there will likely be fewer vaccines given over Memorial Day weekend, both because doses given are declining and because fewer people will likely get vaccinated over the holiday. However, to what extent fewer people get vaccinated over the holiday won't be known until the forecast is closed, as the full extent doesn't show up for 2 days, based on previous holidays. I will guess that maybe 0.6M to 0.8M fewer people than expected will be vaccinated this long weekend. Even if 0.5M fewer than expected don't get vaccinated, just from the daily decline alone, I think the final number will probably go <170M. My current best guess is that the final number will be between 169.0M and 170.0M. @CJH, I don't think it's likely that the forecast will end up >170M.
166.3m plus 1m backlog = 167.3m 3 days reporting left. Current rate just under 800k Will be close to 170m threshold. It all hinges on the accuracy of my assumption on backlog reporting!
Looks like the final count for May 31st will be near 170M so it's hard to pick a bin.
Looking close, though 170 favored because of data lag. We'll see.
On the edge on this one but I think @CJH, @timothy_chan, and @gregorcb has the right idea here, among others who are forecasting the 170 bin. @TMelvin was vying the 170 bin for a while, too.

Today's reported doses were ~0.6M lower than last week's on the same day. Only 0.6M added today to the total for this forecast, and this is one of the higher 4 reporting days of the week. Either people are already getting ready for Memorial Day weekend, or the age 12-15 bump is over. Either way, I would sincerely doubt that the next 4 days are going to be much higher than today and will likely be lower.

I'm assuming the daily vaccination rate will continue to decrease and we won't see more than 170M vaccinated people. This also assumes that there won't be a correction due to reporting error (Though, I didn't do the research about the base rate for such a correction).
165.1m plus 1m backlog = 166.1m 5 reporting days to go 170m threshold = 3.9m = 0.78m per day Current rate =0.8m per day

165.1M as of 5/26. Average of 0.84M/day added in the past week. As of yesterday, 0.86M/day. 3 days ago, 0.88M/day. 5 days ago, 0.8M/day, 0.7M/day the week before that. The number of doses reported today represents a decline over the same day last week and continues a downward trend that has been only slightly interrupted by vaccinating children ages 12 to 15. 165.1M + 8 days (inc. 3 back reporting days) * 0.82M/day (allowing only a slight decline) = 171.5. Without 3 Memorial Day weekend days, we get to 165.1M + 5 * 0.82M = 169.2M. It would seem likely that 0.8M people could be added over the 3 Memorial Day weekend days, but it's not certain whether the average/day won't fall lower than 0.8M. It's getting too close to call.

Average of 0.86M/day added in the past week. As of 2 days ago, 0.88M/day. As of 4 days ago, 0.8M/day, and 0.7M/day the week before that. 6 days left in forecast + 3 for back reporting. 164.4M (total as of 5/25) + 9 * 0.86M/day = 172.1M, identical to my forecast 2 days ago. Again, the question is what will happen on Memorial Day weekend. Suppose Wed. through Friday add 0.86M/day, and that the 3 back reporting days add 0.8M/day. That brings us to 169.4M. So Memorial Day weekend vaccination rates would have to be almost zero to stay under 170M. So I think it's time to update, @CJH. Many in the crowd don't add 3 back reporting days; we saw this in the forecasts in the last round that were close to a forecast bin limit. I wonder whether the crowd so strongly favors <170M in part because of this. But it's clear today (and I should have realized before) that >170M is very likely. It's still possible that vaccination rates could fall off over the next 3 days, so this should be watched closely. Update: I adjusted to 45%/55% because of the uncertainty over declining rates over the next few days. And I see your forecast isn't too different from that!

It's looking like the total will be very close to 170M. I'm assuming there will be declining participation now that the initial spike of 12-16 year olds is over.
I think >170M would likely be reached if Memorial Day weekend weren't coming up.

0.88M/day added in the past week. A lot of kids must be getting vaccinated. As of 2 days ago, 0.8M/day. 0.7M/day added the week before that. Say, 0.8M/day more for the rest of the forecast. 8 more days left in forecast + 3 for back reporting. 163.31M as of 5/23 + 0.8M/day * 11 days = 172.1M. Would need to stay under an average of 0.61M/day to stay under 170M at this point. When will the numbers start falling again?

0.8M/day added in the past week. 0.7M/day added the week before that. 11 more days left in forecast + 3 for back reporting. 160.2M as of 5/20 + 0.8M*14 = 171.4M. 160.2M + 0.7M*14 = 170.0M. Will the numbers start falling again?

Updating. Starting probably early next week, kids age 12 to 15 will be eligible. There are ~16.8M (estimate) in this age group. Recent surveys have said that ~29% of parents are eager to have their kids vaccinated as soon as they're eligible. 16.8M * 0.3 = 5M, so perhaps the total this month will be boosted by ~5M children. https://www.npr.org/sections/coronavirus-live-updates/2021/05/04/993519402/pfizer-says-fda-will-soon-authorize-covid-19-vaccine-for-12-15-age-group https://www.nytimes.com/2021/05/06/health/vaccine-children.html
148.5m today. Add 2m for backlog reporting = 150.8m 25 days to go Thresholds: 170m = 770k per day 180m = 1.15m per day 190m = 1.6m per day

Average daily doses administered are decreasing by ~0.4M/day/week. If one projects that decline linearly out to May 31, only about 85k people/day would be receiving vaccines. However, children age 12-15 will be eligible to take the vaccine starting as early as next week. That will add a pool of almost 17M people eligible to take the vaccine, of which up to ~70% or ~12M may get the vaccine. On the other hand, vaccine hesitancy is strongest among young adults.

If looking at adults alone 170 million would be about 68% of the eligible population. Based on polls I'm skeptical it gets close to that high in the coming month. There are a lot of people who are "wait and see" on the polls, and while some of them may be convinced I think that'll be a long term process over the summer, maybe convincing half or so of those people. According to the poll linked below 62% of people have gotten it or will get it ASAP.
